Example dataset

Regression predicting tchcomm using tchhappy, public, and their interaction.

> #####################################################################
> # Creating interaction term
> l5_2$cross_nocenter=l5_2$tchhappy*l5_2$public
> 
> mreg1=lm(tchcomm~tchhappy+public+cross_nocenter, data=l5_2) #run multiple linear regression predicting tchcoom using tchhappy, public and their interaction.
> summary(mreg1)
TRUE

TRUE 
TRUE Call:
TRUE lm(formula = tchcomm ~ tchhappy + public + cross_nocenter, data = l5_2)
TRUE 
TRUE Standardized Coefficients::
TRUE    (Intercept)       tchhappy         public cross_nocenter 
TRUE             NA           0.53          -0.17          -0.13
> # Intercept (2.23) = average outcome for reference group (private school) with zero tchhappy, sig (p < .05)
> # slope 1 related tchhappy (.82) = the effect of tchhappy on tchcomm for private school, sig (p <.05)
> # slope 2 related public (-2.87) = mean difference in outcome between focal (public) and reference (private) groups with zero tchhappy, sig
> # slope 3 related to interaction (-.22) = difference on slope regarding tchhappy on tch comm betwen focal and reference groups, ns

WRITE-UP

The overall model was statistically significant (F(3,958) = 122, p < .5), with the R-squared value of .28. An intercept was 2.23, which was statistically significant (t(958) = 4.01, p < .05). This indicates that an average tchcomm for private schools with zero happiness was 2.23. An estimated slope regarding teacher happiness was .82, which was statistically significant (t(958) = 7.25, p < .05). This indicates that average tchcomm for private school was significantly increased by .82, for every additional increase in tchhappy, after controlling for other variables. The slope regarding public was statistically significant (t(958) = -4.87, p < .05), suggesting that mean tchcomm for pubic school with zero happiness was significantly lower than one for private schools with zero happiness by 2.87. However, no interaction between school type and tchhappy was found to be staitstically (t(958) = -1.85, p = .06).

#1. Centering of tchhappy #2. Creating interaction term with centered tchhappy and public 

> #####################################################################
> 
> l5_2$center_tchhappy = l5_2$tchhappy-mean(l5_2$tchhappy, trim=0, na.rm=TRUE) #centering the continuous variable
> l5_2$cross_center=l5_2$center_tchhappy*l5_2$public #creating an interaction with centered variable and dummy variable
> 
> mreg2=lm(tchcomm~center_tchhappy+public+cross_center, data=l5_2) 
> summary(mreg2) # provide summary statistics saved in mreg2

WRITE-UP

The overall model was statistically significant (F(3,958) = 122, p < .5), with the R-squared value of .28. An intercept was 2.23, which was statistically significant (t(958) = 4.01, p < .05). This indicates that an average tchcomm for private schools was 2.36 with an average tchhappy. An estimated slope regarding teacher happiness was .82, which was statistically significant (t(958) = 7.25, p < .05). This indicates that average tchcomm for private school was significantly increased by .82, for every additional increase in tchhappy, after controlling for other variables. The slope regarding public was statistically significant (t(958) = -4.87, p < .05), suggesting that mean tchcomm for pubic school with an average happiness was significantly lower than one for private schools with an average happiness by 2.90. However, no interaction between school type and tchhappy was found to be staitstically (t(958) = -1.85, p = .06).

> # Creating an interaction plot
> 
> l5_2$public=factor(l5_2$public, 
+                                 labels=c("private", "public")) 
> library("ggplot2")
> Plot.center_interaction<-ggplot(data=l5_2, aes(x=center_tchhappy, y=tchcomm, color=public))+
+    geom_point()+
+     geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)+
+     ylab("tchcomm")+
+     xlab("tchhappy")+
+     ggtitle("Tchcomm and Tchhappy by School Type [Public vs Private]")+
+     theme_bw()
> Plot.center_interaction

>
